><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39=
;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:1=
50%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margi=
n-bottom:0px;">Unfortunately for Kutler, one of the MSNBC staffers who took=
 issue with the
changes was Maddow, herself. And rather than air her concerns constructivel=
y in private, she decided to put her boss on public blast. On Monday night,=
 she took the =E2=80=9Cpersonal privilege=E2=80=9D of addressing the matter=
 <em>on her show</em>: =E2=80=9CI do not want to lose [Reid] as a colleague=
 here at MSNBC, and personally, I think it is a bad mistake to let her walk=
 out the door,=E2=80=9D Maddow said, later adding that it was =E2=80=9Cunne=
rving to see that on a network where we=E2=80=99ve got two=E2=80=94count =
=E2=80=99em, two=E2=80=94nonwhite hosts in
primetime, both of our nonwhite hosts in primetime are losing their shows. =
=E2=80=A6 And that feels worse than bad, no matter who replaces them. That =
feels indefensible, and I do not defend it.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:=
0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Ma=
ddow then went on to condemn the firing of the production teams, stating th=
at the decision to have them reapply for new jobs =E2=80=9Chas never happen=
ed at this scale in this way before, =E2=80=A6 presumably because it=E2=80=
=99s not the right
way to treat people, and it=E2=80=99s inefficient, and it=E2=80=99s unneces=
sary, and it kind of drops the bottom out of whether or not people feel lik=
e this is a good place to work.=E2=80=9D Finally, Maddow seemed to issue a =
direct challenge to Kutler: =E2=80=9CWe want to grow and succeed and reach =
more people than ever and be resilient and stay here forever. I also believ=
e =E2=80=A6 that the way to get there is by treating people well, finding g=
ood people, good colleagues, doing good work with them, and then having the=
ir back. That
we could do a lot better on=E2=80=94a lot better.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;">Besides the hundreds of thousands of elderly loyal viewers who had no e=
arthly idea what the fuck their favorite political commentator was talking =
about, it initially seemed like Maddow had succeeded in her ostensible goal=
 of fomenting a <strong>Ronna McDaniel</strong>=E2=80=93style insurrection.=
 A year ago, as you might recall, Maddow and the irascible <strong>Chuck
Todd</strong> had slammed NBC News brass for hiring the former R.N.C. chair=
 as a contributor, catalyzing a stupid daylong, <em>Dead Poets Society</em>=
-style desk-jumping cascade in which nearly <em>every </em>MSNBC anchor too=
k a turn dunking on the suits at 30 Rock. It worked: Ronna was fired <em>da=
ys </em>later.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">This time around, however, the response =
inside the network to Maddow=E2=80=99s chest-thumping was more
skeptical. After all, her critique of the network glossed over a few import=
ant details that did not go unnoticed by her colleagues, including several =
other anchors. Most obviously, Reid was being replaced at 7 p.m. by another=
 Black woman (Symone), a Black man (Steele), and the <em>first </em>Latina =
woman (Menendez) to host an MSNBC primetime show in the network=E2=80=99s h=
istory. Not to put <em>too</em> fine a point on it, but the =E2=80=9Ctwo, c=
ount =E2=80=99em two, nonwhite hosts=E2=80=9D were actually being replaced =
by
<em>three</em>=E2=80=94count =E2=80=99em <em>three</em>=E2=80=94nonwhite ho=
sts. In her diatribe, Maddow also claimed that the ouster of the hosts =E2=
=80=9Cwas worse than bad, no matter who replaces them=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94but =
why didn=E2=80=99t <em>that </em>matter? And was it really =E2=80=9Cindefen=
sible=E2=80=9D to make space for three anchors of color whose chemistry mig=
ht conceivably enhance the network=E2=80=99s popularity at a time when its =
ratings have been in the gutter?</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;=
">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Several
of Maddow=E2=80=99s colleagues also noted the peculiarity of the star ancho=
r=E2=80=99s <em>cri de coeur </em>on behalf of the 30 Rock proletariat. In =
all, roughly 125 production staffers will be laid off and invited to reappl=
y for about 110 positions=E2=80=94not ideal, sure, but pretty good for a do=
wnsizing industry. Indeed, CNN now routinely lays off <em>hundreds </em>of =
its employees on a near-annual basis while offering no similar job posts.=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin:
0;margin-bottom:0px;">More to the point, Maddow seemed to miss an obvious i=
rony of her critique: She gets paid <em>$25 million a year</em> to effectiv=
ely work <em>one day a week</em>, an absurdly misaligned salary that allows=
 her to comfortably shuttle between her Manhattan apartment and pre-Civil W=
ar farmhouse retreat in the Berkshires, but puts a financial burden on MSNB=
C to stringently manage the unit economics of every other hour in primetime=
=2E Put another way, her annual salary is roughly
equivalent to the combined salary of about=E2=80=94go figure=E2=80=94125 pr=
oduction staffers.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p=
 style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Of course, NBCUniversal decided long=
 ago that the Maddow imprimatur was worth all that and then some (recall, M=
addow=E2=80=99s salary used to be <em>$30 million </em>a year, and she stil=
l owns most of her I.P.). But that now seems like the arithmetic of a bygon=
e era=E2=80=94and one probably exacerbated by <strong>Ari Emanuel</strong> =
and
<strong>Mark Shapiro</strong>=E2=80=99s negotiating tactics and <strong>Jef=
f Shell</strong>=E2=80=99s anxieties. In those days, NBCU suits largely con=
vinced themselves that Maddow <em>was </em>MSNBC and the network would lose=
 viewership and distribution agreement leverage without her. These days, of=
 course, MSNBC is being pushed off to sea with other declining cable assets=
=2E It isn=E2=80=99t their problem anymor=
e.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bo=
ttom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">In this brave
new world, how valuable is a talent who now brings in only 2 million viewer=
s for one hour a week, and reserves the right to occasionally fly off the h=
andle and nuke her bosses? It=E2=80=99s an unknowable question, on some lev=
el, since Maddow occupies a market of one. On another level, of course, the=
 abundant challenges are clear. In the Kutler era, MSNBC will be required t=
o stabilize ratings with less-expensive talent, all in the hopes that SpinC=
o C.E.O. <strong>Mark Lazarus </strong>can manage the
decline of advertising rates and affiliate fees in the cord-cutting era. An=
d while everyone wishes them well on this journey, it=E2=80=99s all but ine=
vitable that there will be significant bumps along the way.=C2=A0</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Maddow =
may have a point about =E2=80=9Ctreating people well=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9C=
having their back,=E2=80=9D but terminally declining industries aren=E2=80=
=99t Montessori schools=E2=80=94shit gets real. In the increasingly ruthles=
s world of cable news, anchors who
don=E2=80=99t rate won=E2=80=99t be sent off to sinecures; budgets will con=
